long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 1272673 journalctl output for three suspends
Description of problem: Most times when I suspend my laptop, the suspend process takes an abnormally long time
Version-Release number of selected component (if applicable): Kernel 4.10.10
How reproducible: Nearly always
Steps to Reproduce: 1. Suspend using log-out menu item or suspend application
Actual results: Most times suspend takes over 30 seconds, and an error appears on syslog.
Expected results: Suspend in under 5 seconds, no error on syslog.
Additional info:
An update to Fedora over the last couple of weeks appears to have negatively affected the ability of my laptop to suspend to disk.
System information: Lenovo Yoga 2 Pro with i7-4500U processor Haswell architecture Fedora 25 with kernel 4.10.10-200.fc25.x86_64 #1 SMP Thu Apr 13 01:11:51 XFCE No external devices plugged in
Attempt suspend using "Log out" menu item or suspend application. Two different outcomes ensue: 1/ Normal suspend with normal resume 2/ Abnormal delay of over 30 seconds to suspend then normal resume
The abnormal suspend is by far the most frequent. It takes from 30 seconds to well over one minute to screen blank and then another 10 or so seconds to keyboard backlight off and the power light blinking to indicate suspend mode. During the delay the system is unresponsive - the cursor does not even move in response to gestures on the trackpad.
I have included output from journalctl showing three suspends, the first one normal and the last two abnormal. The problem appears to be signalled by usbhid 2-6:1.0: suspend error -5 and subsequent output. I have no idea what this indicates.
Suspend has been fast recently so I'm closing this.
